From: PS4 Linux Baikal Port <noreply@ps4-linux>
Subject: [PATCH] sky2: extend Aeolia PS4 quirks to also cover Baikal and Belize GBE

Our existing 0001-sky2-ps4-quirks.patch (forward-ported from feeRnt's 5.4
PS4 stack via crashniels' 6.15 tree) registers the Baikal GBE PCI ID
(0x90d8) in sky2_id_table so the driver matches the device, but it gates
the three PS4-specific behavior tweaks on `device == AEOLIA_GBE` only.
Result: Baikal binds the driver, then takes the wrong code paths:

  - sky2_reset hits the generic Yukon init path (Baikal needs the same
    pre-reset register pokes Aeolia does, otherwise the chip is left
    in a state where MSI delivery silently drops)
  - sky2_reset attempts a PHY reset (which hangs the chip on PS4 — the
    integrated southbridge PHY does not respond to standard reset)
  - sky2_probe defaults phy_addr to PHY_ADDR_MARV instead of 1 (PS4's
    integrated GBE has its real PHY at addr 1; PHY_ADDR_MARV finds
    nothing and the link never comes up)

Reference: rmuxnet did the equivalent extension on his 7.0 tree as
commit 846b0b28 ("sky2: experimental PS4 Baikal GBE support") on branch
ps4-baikal-ethernet-experiment, plus included BELIZE_GBE for symmetry.
We cherry-pick the same idea here for our 6.x stack — three textual
changes to sky2.c, each adding `|| pdev->device == BAIKAL_GBE` (and the
corresponding BELIZE_GBE clause) to the existing AEOLIA_GBE conditions.

This is the minimum change needed to make Baikal GBE actually link up
through the existing sky2 Aeolia-style init sequence. If the chip turns
out to need additional Baikal-specific quirks (e.g. SPM-based MAC
address fetch, different MSI vector layout), those go in follow-up
patches; this is the "treat Baikal like Aeolia" foundation.

Credit: rmuxnet/ps4-linux-12xx 846b0b28 — pattern adapted to our 6.x
tree.

---
--- a/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
+++ b/drivers/net/ethernet/marvell/sky2.c
@@ -3245,7 +3245,9 @@ static void sky2_reset(struct sky2_hw *hw)

 	#ifdef CONFIG_X86_PS4
 	if (pdev->vendor == PCI_VENDOR_ID_SONY &&
-	    pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_AEOLIA_GBE) {
+	    (pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_AEOLIA_GBE ||
+	     pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BELIZE_GBE ||
+	     pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BAIKAL_GBE)) {
 		u32 val1, val2;

 		sky2_write32(hw, 0x60, 0x32100);
@@ -3327,8 +3329,10 @@ static void sky2_reset(struct sky2_hw *hw)

 	#ifdef CONFIG_X86_PS4
 	if (pdev->vendor == PCI_VENDOR_ID_SONY &&
-	    pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_AEOLIA_GBE) {
-		; /* Do not perform phy resets on aeolia, it will hang */
+	    (pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_AEOLIA_GBE ||
+	     pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BELIZE_GBE ||
+	     pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BAIKAL_GBE)) {
+		; /* Do not perform phy resets on PS4, it will hang */
 	} else
 	#endif

@@ -4999,8 +5003,10 @@ static int sky2_probe(struct pci_dev *pdev, const struct pci_device_id *ent)
 	hw->phy_addr = PHY_ADDR_MARV;
 	#ifdef CONFIG_X86_PS4
 	if (pdev->vendor == PCI_VENDOR_ID_SONY &&
-	    pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_AEOLIA_GBE) {
-		/* aeolia supports some sort of "l2 switch" */
+	    (pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_AEOLIA_GBE ||
+	     pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BELIZE_GBE ||
+	     pdev->device == PCI_DEVICE_ID_SONY_BAIKAL_GBE)) {
+		/* PS4 supports some sort of "l2 switch" */
 		/* it has normal phy at addr 1 with a possibly-active switch at addr 2 */
 		hw->phy_addr = 1;
 	}
